</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Magnetic resonance (MR) imaging has emerged as an important imaging modality for the assessment of cirrhosis and its complications. Faster sequences now allow high-quality liver imaging with high intrinsic soft-tissue contrast. Automated contrast detection methods in combination with faster sequences allow reproducible capture of the arterial phase, which is essential for the detection and characterization of hepatocellular carcinoma. The lack of ionizing radiation permits routine use of gadolinium-enhanced three-dimensional (3D) fat-suppressed multiphasic imaging with high temporal and spatial resolution. In addition, MR imaging allows simultaneous evaluation of the background liver parenchyma and the liver lesions with the combined use of sequences that include T2-weighted sequences, T1-weighted sequences (including chemical shift imaging), echoplanar diffusion-weighted sequences, dynamic gadolinium-enhanced 3D multiphasic imaging, and liver-specific delayed phase sequences (if contrast agents with hepatobiliary excretion are used). The combination of findings from different sequences often helps pinpoint the nature of the liver abnormalities.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095508">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095508">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c01x.jpeg" height="410" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f1-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Drawing illustrates the concept of stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC in cirrhosis. According to this concept, a regenerative nodule <i>(RN)</i> increases in size and cellularity with changes of atypia and is transformed into a dysplastic nodule <i>(DN).</i> A focus of HCC may develop within a dysplastic nodule; this focus can progress to a small HCC and then to a large (&gt;2-cm) HCC. Simultaneously, the nodule develops its own neovascularity, which is necessary to support the rapid growth of the nodule into HCC. Differences in color indicate subnodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f1-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g10a.jpeg" height="1132" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Small and large HCCs. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a large, dominant, mostly hypointense nodule in segment VI of the liver (arrow). The liver is cirrhotic, with splenomegaly also being present. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows faint heterogeneous enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow), with a smaller, intensely enhancing nodule now apparent in segment V of the liver (arrowhead). In retrospect, this second nodule was isointense on the T2-weighted image (cf <b>a</b>). <b>(c)</b> On an axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image, the dominant nodule (arrow) shows washout of contrast material with capsular enhancement, findings that are consistent with a large HCC. The smaller nodule (arrowhead) has become heterogeneous, indicating washout of contrast material, and shows no clear capsular enhancement, findings that are consistent with a small HCC. Drawing illustrates the locations of the small HCC and the large HCC (both shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f10a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g10b.jpeg" height="1143" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Small and large HCCs. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a large, dominant, mostly hypointense nodule in segment VI of the liver (arrow). The liver is cirrhotic, with splenomegaly also being present. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows faint heterogeneous enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow), with a smaller, intensely enhancing nodule now apparent in segment V of the liver (arrowhead). In retrospect, this second nodule was isointense on the T2-weighted image (cf <b>a</b>). <b>(c)</b> On an axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image, the dominant nodule (arrow) shows washout of contrast material with capsular enhancement, findings that are consistent with a large HCC. The smaller nodule (arrowhead) has become heterogeneous, indicating washout of contrast material, and shows no clear capsular enhancement, findings that are consistent with a small HCC. Drawing illustrates the locations of the small HCC and the large HCC (both shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f10b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c10c.jpeg" height="827" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f10c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Small and large HCCs. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a large, dominant, mostly hypointense nodule in segment VI of the liver (arrow). The liver is cirrhotic, with splenomegaly also being present. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows faint heterogeneous enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow), with a smaller, intensely enhancing nodule now apparent in segment V of the liver (arrowhead). In retrospect, this second nodule was isointense on the T2-weighted image (cf <b>a</b>). <b>(c)</b> On an axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image, the dominant nodule (arrow) shows washout of contrast material with capsular enhancement, findings that are consistent with a large HCC. The smaller nodule (arrowhead) has become heterogeneous, indicating washout of contrast material, and shows no clear capsular enhancement, findings that are consistent with a small HCC. Drawing illustrates the locations of the small HCC and the large HCC (both shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f10c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g11a.jpeg" height="1243" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Multiple HCCs in a patient with known hepatitis C virus infection and an elevated α-fetoprotein level. <b>(a)</b> Axial single-shot T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with a dominant low-signal-intensity nodule. Note the perihepatic ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows numerous nodules with variable enhancement throughout the cirrhotic liver. On delayed phase images, most of these nodules showed washout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f11a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g11b.jpeg" height="1249" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Multiple HCCs in a patient with known hepatitis C virus infection and an elevated α-fetoprotein level. <b>(a)</b> Axial single-shot T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with a dominant low-signal-intensity nodule. Note the perihepatic ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows numerous nodules with variable enhancement throughout the cirrhotic liver. On delayed phase images, most of these nodules showed washout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f11b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g12a.jpeg" height="1284" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f12a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Segmental diffuse HCC with portal vein invasion. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with perihepatic ascites and a thrombosed right portal vein (arrow). No tumor is visible. <b>(b)</b> Arterial phase image shows enhancement within segment VI of the liver, along with arterial enhancement of the right portal vein (arrow), a finding that suggests tumor thrombus. <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered image from delayed phase imaging data shows washout of contrast material from the right portal vein (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered image from arterial phase imaging data more clearly depicts the enhancement seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f12a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g12b.jpeg" height="1274" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f12b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Segmental diffuse HCC with portal vein invasion. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with perihepatic ascites and a thrombosed right portal vein (arrow). No tumor is visible. <b>(b)</b> Arterial phase image shows enhancement within segment VI of the liver, along with arterial enhancement of the right portal vein (arrow), a finding that suggests tumor thrombus. <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered image from delayed phase imaging data shows washout of contrast material from the right portal vein (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered image from arterial phase imaging data more clearly depicts the enhancement seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f12b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c12c.jpeg" height="908" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f12c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Segmental diffuse HCC with portal vein invasion. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with perihepatic ascites and a thrombosed right portal vein (arrow). No tumor is visible. <b>(b)</b> Arterial phase image shows enhancement within segment VI of the liver, along with arterial enhancement of the right portal vein (arrow), a finding that suggests tumor thrombus. <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered image from delayed phase imaging data shows washout of contrast material from the right portal vein (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered image from arterial phase imaging data more clearly depicts the enhancement seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f12c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12d-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c12d.jpeg" height="913" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f12d-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Segmental diffuse HCC with portal vein invasion. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with perihepatic ascites and a thrombosed right portal vein (arrow). No tumor is visible. <b>(b)</b> Arterial phase image shows enhancement within segment VI of the liver, along with arterial enhancement of the right portal vein (arrow), a finding that suggests tumor thrombus. <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered image from delayed phase imaging data shows washout of contrast material from the right portal vein (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered image from arterial phase imaging data more clearly depicts the enhancement seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f12d-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g13a.jpeg" height="1299" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Large HCC in a noncirrhotic liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a large, predominantly hyperintense HCC within a noncirrhotic liver (note the smooth liver edges and lack of regenerative nodules). The spleen is normal in size, and no ascites is present. <b>(b)</b> On an axial fat-suppressed GRE T1-weighted MR image, the HCC is predominantly hypointense with a small hemorrhage (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows intense heterogeneous enhancement of the HCC. <b>(d)</b> Axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material washout with capsular enhancement of the HCC. Note that the hemorrhage within the HCC is not enhanced (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f13a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g13b.jpeg" height="1293" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Large HCC in a noncirrhotic liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a large, predominantly hyperintense HCC within a noncirrhotic liver (note the smooth liver edges and lack of regenerative nodules). The spleen is normal in size, and no ascites is present. <b>(b)</b> On an axial fat-suppressed GRE T1-weighted MR image, the HCC is predominantly hypointense with a small hemorrhage (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows intense heterogeneous enhancement of the HCC. <b>(d)</b> Axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material washout with capsular enhancement of the HCC. Note that the hemorrhage within the HCC is not enhanced (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f13b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g13c.jpeg" height="1199" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Large HCC in a noncirrhotic liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a large, predominantly hyperintense HCC within a noncirrhotic liver (note the smooth liver edges and lack of regenerative nodules). The spleen is normal in size, and no ascites is present. <b>(b)</b> On an axial fat-suppressed GRE T1-weighted MR image, the HCC is predominantly hypointense with a small hemorrhage (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows intense heterogeneous enhancement of the HCC. <b>(d)</b> Axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material washout with capsular enhancement of the HCC. Note that the hemorrhage within the HCC is not enhanced (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f13c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13d-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g13d.jpeg" height="1213" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13d-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span> Large HCC in a noncirrhotic liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a large, predominantly hyperintense HCC within a noncirrhotic liver (note the smooth liver edges and lack of regenerative nodules). The spleen is normal in size, and no ascites is present. <b>(b)</b> On an axial fat-suppressed GRE T1-weighted MR image, the HCC is predominantly hypointense with a small hemorrhage (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows intense heterogeneous enhancement of the HCC. <b>(d)</b> Axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material washout with capsular enhancement of the HCC. Note that the hemorrhage within the HCC is not enhanced (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f13d-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c02a.jpeg" height="667" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f2a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> HCC with regenerative nodules in a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows a cirrhotic liver with numerous regenerative nodules and a larger dominant nodule (arrow) that is consistent with HCC. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows regenerative nodules <i>(RN)</i> surrounded by fibrous septa, findings that indicate cirrhosis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) of a specimen from the dominant nodule in <b>a</b> shows abnormal hepatocytes, increased cellularity and cell layers, and variable-sized nuclei, findings consistent with HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f2a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c02b.jpeg" height="921" width="1215" aria-labelledby="f2b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> HCC with regenerative nodules in a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows a cirrhotic liver with numerous regenerative nodules and a larger dominant nodule (arrow) that is consistent with HCC. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows regenerative nodules <i>(RN)</i> surrounded by fibrous septa, findings that indicate cirrhosis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) of a specimen from the dominant nodule in <b>a</b> shows abnormal hepatocytes, increased cellularity and cell layers, and variable-sized nuclei, findings consistent with HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f2b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c02c.jpeg" height="971" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f2c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> HCC with regenerative nodules in a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows a cirrhotic liver with numerous regenerative nodules and a larger dominant nodule (arrow) that is consistent with HCC. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows regenerative nodules <i>(RN)</i> surrounded by fibrous septa, findings that indicate cirrhosis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) of a specimen from the dominant nodule in <b>a</b> shows abnormal hepatocytes, increased cellularity and cell layers, and variable-sized nuclei, findings consistent with HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f2c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g03a.jpeg" height="1188" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Typical MR imaging examination of the liver. <b>(a)</b> On an axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image, the spleen is much brighter than the liver. This sequence is considered to be sensitive for the depiction of solid liver lesions, which typically follow the signal intensity of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase gradient-echo (GRE) T1-weighted MR image obtained as part of a dual GRE (chemical shift) sequence shows T1 information as well as hemorrhage and fatty infiltration within the liver and nodules. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained with bolus tracking shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is the single most important sequence for the detection and characterization of focal liver lesions. <b>(d)</b> Axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained 2–5 minutes after contrast material injection shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is essential for the further characterization of liver lesions detected during the arterial phase. <b>(e)</b> Volume-rendered image from dynamic gadolinium-enhanced arterial phase imaging data obtained in a different patient shows the celiac trunk <i>(ct)</i>, duodenal artery <i>(da)</i>, hepatic artery <i>(ha)</i>, left gastric artery <i>(lga)</i>, left hepatic artery <i>(lha)</i>, right hepatic artery <i>(rha)</i>, and splenic artery <i>(sa)</i>. <b>(f)</b> Volume-rendered image from data obtained during the delayed phase shows the aorta <i>(ao)</i>, inferior vena cava <i>(ivc)</i>, left hepatic vein <i>(lhv)</i>, middle hepatic vein <i>(mhv)</i>, main portal vein <i>(mpv)</i>, right hepatic vein <i>(rhv)</i>, superior mesenteric vein <i>(smv),</i> and splenic vein <i>(sv)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f3a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g03b.jpeg" height="1173" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Typical MR imaging examination of the liver. <b>(a)</b> On an axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image, the spleen is much brighter than the liver. This sequence is considered to be sensitive for the depiction of solid liver lesions, which typically follow the signal intensity of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase gradient-echo (GRE) T1-weighted MR image obtained as part of a dual GRE (chemical shift) sequence shows T1 information as well as hemorrhage and fatty infiltration within the liver and nodules. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained with bolus tracking shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is the single most important sequence for the detection and characterization of focal liver lesions. <b>(d)</b> Axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained 2–5 minutes after contrast material injection shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is essential for the further characterization of liver lesions detected during the arterial phase. <b>(e)</b> Volume-rendered image from dynamic gadolinium-enhanced arterial phase imaging data obtained in a different patient shows the celiac trunk <i>(ct)</i>, duodenal artery <i>(da)</i>, hepatic artery <i>(ha)</i>, left gastric artery <i>(lga)</i>, left hepatic artery <i>(lha)</i>, right hepatic artery <i>(rha)</i>, and splenic artery <i>(sa)</i>. <b>(f)</b> Volume-rendered image from data obtained during the delayed phase shows the aorta <i>(ao)</i>, inferior vena cava <i>(ivc)</i>, left hepatic vein <i>(lhv)</i>, middle hepatic vein <i>(mhv)</i>, main portal vein <i>(mpv)</i>, right hepatic vein <i>(rhv)</i>, superior mesenteric vein <i>(smv),</i> and splenic vein <i>(sv)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f3b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g03c.jpeg" height="1184" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Typical MR imaging examination of the liver. <b>(a)</b> On an axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image, the spleen is much brighter than the liver. This sequence is considered to be sensitive for the depiction of solid liver lesions, which typically follow the signal intensity of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase gradient-echo (GRE) T1-weighted MR image obtained as part of a dual GRE (chemical shift) sequence shows T1 information as well as hemorrhage and fatty infiltration within the liver and nodules. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained with bolus tracking shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is the single most important sequence for the detection and characterization of focal liver lesions. <b>(d)</b> Axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained 2–5 minutes after contrast material injection shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is essential for the further characterization of liver lesions detected during the arterial phase. <b>(e)</b> Volume-rendered image from dynamic gadolinium-enhanced arterial phase imaging data obtained in a different patient shows the celiac trunk <i>(ct)</i>, duodenal artery <i>(da)</i>, hepatic artery <i>(ha)</i>, left gastric artery <i>(lga)</i>, left hepatic artery <i>(lha)</i>, right hepatic artery <i>(rha)</i>, and splenic artery <i>(sa)</i>. <b>(f)</b> Volume-rendered image from data obtained during the delayed phase shows the aorta <i>(ao)</i>, inferior vena cava <i>(ivc)</i>, left hepatic vein <i>(lhv)</i>, middle hepatic vein <i>(mhv)</i>, main portal vein <i>(mpv)</i>, right hepatic vein <i>(rhv)</i>, superior mesenteric vein <i>(smv),</i> and splenic vein <i>(sv)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f3c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3d-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g03d.jpeg" height="1172" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3d-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Typical MR imaging examination of the liver. <b>(a)</b> On an axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image, the spleen is much brighter than the liver. This sequence is considered to be sensitive for the depiction of solid liver lesions, which typically follow the signal intensity of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase gradient-echo (GRE) T1-weighted MR image obtained as part of a dual GRE (chemical shift) sequence shows T1 information as well as hemorrhage and fatty infiltration within the liver and nodules. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained with bolus tracking shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is the single most important sequence for the detection and characterization of focal liver lesions. <b>(d)</b> Axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained 2–5 minutes after contrast material injection shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is essential for the further characterization of liver lesions detected during the arterial phase. <b>(e)</b> Volume-rendered image from dynamic gadolinium-enhanced arterial phase imaging data obtained in a different patient shows the celiac trunk <i>(ct)</i>, duodenal artery <i>(da)</i>, hepatic artery <i>(ha)</i>, left gastric artery <i>(lga)</i>, left hepatic artery <i>(lha)</i>, right hepatic artery <i>(rha)</i>, and splenic artery <i>(sa)</i>. <b>(f)</b> Volume-rendered image from data obtained during the delayed phase shows the aorta <i>(ao)</i>, inferior vena cava <i>(ivc)</i>, left hepatic vein <i>(lhv)</i>, middle hepatic vein <i>(mhv)</i>, main portal vein <i>(mpv)</i>, right hepatic vein <i>(rhv)</i>, superior mesenteric vein <i>(smv),</i> and splenic vein <i>(sv)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f3d-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3e-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c03e.jpeg" height="888" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f3e-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span> Typical MR imaging examination of the liver. <b>(a)</b> On an axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image, the spleen is much brighter than the liver. This sequence is considered to be sensitive for the depiction of solid liver lesions, which typically follow the signal intensity of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase gradient-echo (GRE) T1-weighted MR image obtained as part of a dual GRE (chemical shift) sequence shows T1 information as well as hemorrhage and fatty infiltration within the liver and nodules. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained with bolus tracking shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is the single most important sequence for the detection and characterization of focal liver lesions. <b>(d)</b> Axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained 2–5 minutes after contrast material injection shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is essential for the further characterization of liver lesions detected during the arterial phase. <b>(e)</b> Volume-rendered image from dynamic gadolinium-enhanced arterial phase imaging data obtained in a different patient shows the celiac trunk <i>(ct)</i>, duodenal artery <i>(da)</i>, hepatic artery <i>(ha)</i>, left gastric artery <i>(lga)</i>, left hepatic artery <i>(lha)</i>, right hepatic artery <i>(rha)</i>, and splenic artery <i>(sa)</i>. <b>(f)</b> Volume-rendered image from data obtained during the delayed phase shows the aorta <i>(ao)</i>, inferior vena cava <i>(ivc)</i>, left hepatic vein <i>(lhv)</i>, middle hepatic vein <i>(mhv)</i>, main portal vein <i>(mpv)</i>, right hepatic vein <i>(rhv)</i>, superior mesenteric vein <i>(smv),</i> and splenic vein <i>(sv)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f3e-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3f-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c03f.jpeg" height="889" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f3f-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3f</span> Typical MR imaging examination of the liver. <b>(a)</b> On an axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image, the spleen is much brighter than the liver. This sequence is considered to be sensitive for the depiction of solid liver lesions, which typically follow the signal intensity of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase gradient-echo (GRE) T1-weighted MR image obtained as part of a dual GRE (chemical shift) sequence shows T1 information as well as hemorrhage and fatty infiltration within the liver and nodules. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained with bolus tracking shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is the single most important sequence for the detection and characterization of focal liver lesions. <b>(d)</b> Axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted image obtained 2–5 minutes after contrast material injection shows no pathologic findings. This sequence is essential for the further characterization of liver lesions detected during the arterial phase. <b>(e)</b> Volume-rendered image from dynamic gadolinium-enhanced arterial phase imaging data obtained in a different patient shows the celiac trunk <i>(ct)</i>, duodenal artery <i>(da)</i>, hepatic artery <i>(ha)</i>, left gastric artery <i>(lga)</i>, left hepatic artery <i>(lha)</i>, right hepatic artery <i>(rha)</i>, and splenic artery <i>(sa)</i>. <b>(f)</b> Volume-rendered image from data obtained during the delayed phase shows the aorta <i>(ao)</i>, inferior vena cava <i>(ivc)</i>, left hepatic vein <i>(lhv)</i>, middle hepatic vein <i>(mhv)</i>, main portal vein <i>(mpv)</i>, right hepatic vein <i>(rhv)</i>, superior mesenteric vein <i>(smv),</i> and splenic vein <i>(sv)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f3f-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c04x.jpeg" height="605" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f4-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Drawings illustrate how the shape of a cirrhotic liver can be quite variable, with either segmental atrophy or hypertrophy, irregular contours, nodules, and signs of portal hypertension (splenomegaly, collateral vessels and varices, ascites).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f4-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g05a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1530" aria-labelledby="f5a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Developing HCC. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(a)</b>, 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(c)</b> show the gradual development of a small nodule into a large HCC (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> On axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(d)</b>, 1 year later <b>(e)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(f)</b>, the nodule (arrow) increases in size and eventually develops into a large HCC with washout and capsular enhancement. Drawing illustrates the location of a degenerative nodule <i>(DN)</i>, an HCC focus, and a large HCC (all shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f5a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g05b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1565" aria-labelledby="f5b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Developing HCC. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(a)</b>, 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(c)</b> show the gradual development of a small nodule into a large HCC (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> On axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(d)</b>, 1 year later <b>(e)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(f)</b>, the nodule (arrow) increases in size and eventually develops into a large HCC with washout and capsular enhancement. Drawing illustrates the location of a degenerative nodule <i>(DN)</i>, an HCC focus, and a large HCC (all shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f5b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g05c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1530" aria-labelledby="f5c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Developing HCC. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(a)</b>, 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(c)</b> show the gradual development of a small nodule into a large HCC (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> On axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(d)</b>, 1 year later <b>(e)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(f)</b>, the nodule (arrow) increases in size and eventually develops into a large HCC with washout and capsular enhancement. Drawing illustrates the location of a degenerative nodule <i>(DN)</i>, an HCC focus, and a large HCC (all shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f5c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5d-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g05d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1608" aria-labelledby="f5d-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span> Developing HCC. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(a)</b>, 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(c)</b> show the gradual development of a small nodule into a large HCC (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> On axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(d)</b>, 1 year later <b>(e)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(f)</b>, the nodule (arrow) increases in size and eventually develops into a large HCC with washout and capsular enhancement. Drawing illustrates the location of a degenerative nodule <i>(DN)</i>, an HCC focus, and a large HCC (all shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f5d-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5e-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g05e.jpeg" height="1800" width="1478" aria-labelledby="f5e-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5e</span> Developing HCC. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(a)</b>, 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(c)</b> show the gradual development of a small nodule into a large HCC (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> On axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(d)</b>, 1 year later <b>(e)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(f)</b>, the nodule (arrow) increases in size and eventually develops into a large HCC with washout and capsular enhancement. Drawing illustrates the location of a degenerative nodule <i>(DN)</i>, an HCC focus, and a large HCC (all shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f5e-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5f-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c05f.jpeg" height="1280" width="1196" aria-labelledby="f5f-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5f</span> Developing HCC. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(a)</b>, 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(c)</b> show the gradual development of a small nodule into a large HCC (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> On axial 3D delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR images obtained to establish a baseline <b>(d)</b>, 1 year later <b>(e)</b>, and 2 years later <b>(f)</b>, the nodule (arrow) increases in size and eventually develops into a large HCC with washout and capsular enhancement. Drawing illustrates the location of a degenerative nodule <i>(DN)</i>, an HCC focus, and a large HCC (all shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f5f-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g06a.jpeg" height="1275" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Typical (large) HCC. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense dominant nodule larger than 2 cm (arrow) within a cirrhotic liver. Note the numerous small hypointense nodules throughout the liver, findings that represent regenerative nodules. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows washout of contrast material with capsular enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow), findings that are consistent with a large HCC. Numerous small hypointense regenerative nodules are again seen scattered throughout the liver (cf <b>a</b>). Drawing illustrates the location of a large HCC (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f6a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g06b.jpeg" height="1282" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Typical (large) HCC. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense dominant nodule larger than 2 cm (arrow) within a cirrhotic liver. Note the numerous small hypointense nodules throughout the liver, findings that represent regenerative nodules. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows washout of contrast material with capsular enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow), findings that are consistent with a large HCC. Numerous small hypointense regenerative nodules are again seen scattered throughout the liver (cf <b>a</b>). Drawing illustrates the location of a large HCC (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f6b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c06c.jpeg" height="902" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f6c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Typical (large) HCC. <b>(a)</b> Axial standard fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense dominant nodule larger than 2 cm (arrow) within a cirrhotic liver. Note the numerous small hypointense nodules throughout the liver, findings that represent regenerative nodules. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial delayed phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows washout of contrast material with capsular enhancement of the dominant nodule (arrow), findings that are consistent with a large HCC. Numerous small hypointense regenerative nodules are again seen scattered throughout the liver (cf <b>a</b>). Drawing illustrates the location of a large HCC (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f6c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g07a.jpeg" height="1110" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Regenerative nodules. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood echoplanar T2-weighted MR image obtained with a low diffusion gradient and fat suppression shows no hyper-intense lesions in the liver. Splenomegaly is noted, however. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver containing numerous regenerative nodules with variable signal intensity. Note the irregular contours of the liver and the atrophy of segments III and IV. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows no enhancing nodules. Drawing illustrates the location of a regenerative nodule (<i>RN</i>, shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f7a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g07b.jpeg" height="1079" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Regenerative nodules. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood echoplanar T2-weighted MR image obtained with a low diffusion gradient and fat suppression shows no hyper-intense lesions in the liver. Splenomegaly is noted, however. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver containing numerous regenerative nodules with variable signal intensity. Note the irregular contours of the liver and the atrophy of segments III and IV. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows no enhancing nodules. Drawing illustrates the location of a regenerative nodule (<i>RN</i>, shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f7b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c07c.jpeg" height="839" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f7c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Regenerative nodules. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood echoplanar T2-weighted MR image obtained with a low diffusion gradient and fat suppression shows no hyper-intense lesions in the liver. Splenomegaly is noted, however. <b>(b)</b> Axial in-phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver containing numerous regenerative nodules with variable signal intensity. Note the irregular contours of the liver and the atrophy of segments III and IV. <b>(c)</b> Axial 3D arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows no enhancing nodules. Drawing illustrates the location of a regenerative nodule (<i>RN</i>, shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f7c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g08a.jpeg" height="1305" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Nodule-within-a-nodule abnormality. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood echoplanar T2-weighted MR image shows a small hypointense nodule (arrow) containing a smaller high-signal-intensity nodule within a cirrhotic liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase image shows enhancement of the inner nodule and helps confirm the presence of a nodule-within-a-nodule abnormality. Drawing illustrates the location of an HCC focus (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f8a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c08b.jpeg" height="921" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f8b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Nodule-within-a-nodule abnormality. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood echoplanar T2-weighted MR image shows a small hypointense nodule (arrow) containing a smaller high-signal-intensity nodule within a cirrhotic liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase image shows enhancement of the inner nodule and helps confirm the presence of a nodule-within-a-nodule abnormality. Drawing illustrates the location of an HCC focus (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f8b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9a-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05g09a.jpeg" height="1299" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9a-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Small HCC. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows a small enhancing lesion (arrow) in segment VIII of the liver. A second enhancing lesion is seen in a more posterior location in segment VII. Both lesions proved to be HCC at explant correlation. <b>(b)</b> Axial single-shot T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with rounded and irregular edges and peripheral atrophy (indicated by the space between the liver and the abdominal wall). The enhancing lesions that were seen in <b>a</b> are now isointense relative to the liver. Drawing illustrates the location of a small HCC (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows an HCC in segment VIII. Note that the HCC is surrounded by a thin, fibrous capsule (arrows). The background liver is clearly cirrhotic with regenerative nodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f9a-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9b-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c09b.jpeg" height="906" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f9b-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Small HCC. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows a small enhancing lesion (arrow) in segment VIII of the liver. A second enhancing lesion is seen in a more posterior location in segment VII. Both lesions proved to be HCC at explant correlation. <b>(b)</b> Axial single-shot T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with rounded and irregular edges and peripheral atrophy (indicated by the space between the liver and the abdominal wall). The enhancing lesions that were seen in <b>a</b> are now isointense relative to the liver. Drawing illustrates the location of a small HCC (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows an HCC in segment VIII. Note that the HCC is surrounded by a thin, fibrous capsule (arrows). The background liver is clearly cirrhotic with regenerative nodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f9b-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9c-0291637" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095508/asset/images/g09oc05c09c.jpeg" height="721" width="909" aria-labelledby="f9c-0291637" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Small HCC. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase GRE T1-weighted MR image shows a small enhancing lesion (arrow) in segment VIII of the liver. A second enhancing lesion is seen in a more posterior location in segment VII. Both lesions proved to be HCC at explant correlation. <b>(b)</b> Axial single-shot T2-weighted MR image shows a cirrhotic liver with rounded and irregular edges and peripheral atrophy (indicated by the space between the liver and the abdominal wall). The enhancing lesions that were seen in <b>a</b> are now isointense relative to the liver. Drawing illustrates the location of a small HCC (shown in color) in the stepwise carcinogenesis of HCC. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows an HCC in segment VIII. Note that the HCC is surrounded by a thin, fibrous capsule (arrows). The background liver is clearly cirrhotic with regenerative nodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095508&amp;id=f9c-0291637">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0291637" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hussain SM, Semelka RC, Mitchell DG. MR imaging of hepatocellular carcinoma. <em>Magn Reson Imaging Clin N Am</em> 2002;10:31–52.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S1064-9689(03)00048-5">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11998574/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=MR+imaging+of+hepatocellular+carcinoma&amp;author=SM+Hussain&amp;author=RC+Semelka&amp;author=DG+Mitchell&amp;publication_year=2002&amp;journal=Magn+Reson+Imaging+Clin+N+Am&amp;pages=31-52&amp;doi=10.1016%2FS1064-9689%2803%2900048-5&amp;pmid=11998574">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="labe